charity.name: Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
One year ago today I received my last chemo session. I didn’t know that it would be my last. Following a major operation in December 2019, it was confirmed I was cancer free. 

I spend a lot of time thinking about those having to receive treatment this year. Some having to miss treatment, not being able to have someone sat by their side, everyone wearing masks, being afraid of what would happen if you caught COVID. It must be such a horrid experience and nothing like what I experienced. 

I have not fundraised for Macmillan yet this year as I have usually held events with the help of friends. It is all too complicated with social distancing and rule of six.  

If you know me, you will know I like a drink or two. I have decided to give it up for a month. This is a big deal for me. Please support me by giving generously to Macmillan Cancer Support. Their nurses will be the ones supporting the cancer patients whilst they sit for hours on end receiving their treatment. I loved my Macmillan nurse and looked forward to seeing her. They also give amazing advise online among other things. 

I thank my lucky stars and the fabulous NHS that I did not have to have chemo this year.

story:
“Battle Cancer is one day, four nine-minute workouts, one fundraising goal.”

Fraser, Hannah, Omi and Eleanor are joining as a team to raise money for Macmillan Cancer Support in memory of all those who we have lost to the terrible disease, for those who are fighting and those who have overcome. 

Thank you Macmillan for providing incredible care and support to those in need, we are not doing this to win or to be the fittest, we are doing this for you!

Workout 1: Fundraising AMRAP - As Much Raised As Possible. The more you raise, the higher your score! £1 = 1 rep.

Workout 2 & 3: Released 12/10/20. Two 9-minute workouts completed one straight after the other with 5-minutes rest in between, creating a 23-minute challenge.

story:
Battle Cancer is one day, four nine-minute workouts, one fundraising goal.
Set yourself a challenge, give yourself a purpose and take part in an epic day!
Battle Cancer combines playful functional fitness workouts with a teamwork experience like no other. We're not about finding the strongest or fittest, Battle Cancer is a mindset, a community and battling something bigger than us all.

1. Enter as a team of four (all male, all female, or mixed - any combination of gender: 2 men 2 women, 1 man 3 women, 1 woman 3 men. 

2. Fundraise for Macmillan in the lead up to the competition and submit your fundraising total at registration. This will rank you on the leaderboard for your chance to get a leg up on the competition before any fitness takes place!

3. Compete in four 9-minute fitness workouts over the course of the day

4. End on a huge sense of accomplishment

Whether you are participating in the UK, Europe or America - thank you for playing a part in supporting Macmillan.

eventName: The Kings Hill Sports Park Christmas 10k
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation, in memory of my Father and I'd be so grateful for your support.

After witnessing first hand the amazing work and selfless the BHF & team at the Royal Papworth hospital do to help, I have been totally inspired this year to do my part and help.

To try and raise as much a possible this year I am trying to complete the Kings Hill Sports Park Christmas 10k run in 45min. I know first hand how tough this will be given my past run of the Newham 10k.

My personal best was the Newham 10k run where I achieved 1:18. To try and take 33mins off my time, I need support and encouragement and no better way to get this than by you guys parting with your hard earned cash, no matter how small a donation, as it will spur me to achieve the goal and in doing so support the amazing works the BHF.

BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target.

Thanks for your support!

200 Beacon Avenue, 
Kings Hill, West Malling, ME19 4QP

Date: Sunday 20th December 2020

Time: 09:00

Simon

story:
When Elijah was born on the 11th of January 2019, he had to be taken away to the NNUH NICU, where they looked after him as he has spina bifida and had a cyst on the back of his neck which had the volume of half a can of coke.  We ended up spending a week and a half in NNUH, then we got sent to Addenbrookes Hospital in Cambridge for a week before being sent to GOSH in London, where they operated on him at only three weeks old. Dr Thompson did a fantastic job removing the cyst but it didn’t come without its worries and it’s sadness that this was happening to our baby boy. We left hospital a week later, just in time for him to be 1 month old but he got an infection... it eventually cleared up and then from there on things were plain sailing and now nearly two years later our beautiful, perfect, happy baby boy is talking, running and eating for England. 

On his 2nd birthday we are planning to do a sponsored walk around Whitlingham Broads to show how far he has come from a boy who might not have been able to walk to doing all he can now and to thank all the people that looked after our boy and gave him the life he deserves and gave us our ray of sunshine back. 

Thankyou to everyone for saying thanks to them with us.

Love Amy, Harry & Elijah 💙💙

story:
This summer we're taking on GOSH Charity Taskmaster and will be completing hilariously mind-boggling tasks as we prove our fundraising prowess for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity).  

Each Thursday, a new mission will be set and we'll be conjuring up fun and clever ways to complete it so we can be in with the chance of winning the GOSH Charity Taskmaster crown. That's where you come in - the more sponsors we get, the more creative we'll make sure our antics will be!   

With many of GOSH Charity's major fundraising activities cancelled this year, our support has never been more important to make a huge difference to seriously ill children and their families at the hospital.  

Fancy getting in on the action? Take a look at #GOSHTaskmaster and follow @GOSHCharity on Twitter to find out the latest task waiting for you to show off your creative flair.

story:
I started swimming in the sea pool daily about three months ago and I love it. As a personal challenge to myself I told myself I want to keep doing this all through the winter. 

Then I heard about the Polar Bear Challenge and thought why not. If I want to keep getting in anyway then it'll be something to motivate me on the days I have second thoughts. 

The Polar Bear Challenge is basically swimming outdoors right through from November to March in nothing more than a swimming costume. There's different levels of the challenge and, well, I went and registered for the 'Arctic' level. This level requires a two seoerate swims of 250 metres  plus a monthly total of 3000 metres per month, for every month from November to March. 

The water temperature have started dropping and now I'm thinking how am I going to manage getting in the cold water in mid winter never mind swim in it.  

So, more motivation required, let's raise money for cancer research and give me every reason to keep getting in that pool no matter how cold it gets.

eventName: 300k Run throughout November (10k everyday for 30 days)
story:
According to the most accurate forecast from Cancer Research UK, one in two people will develop cancer at some point in their lives.

When you hear this statistic you think to yourself, surely not? And then you take a step back and realise just how many incredible people in your life have been affected by cancer.

This needs to stop!  We need to work together to help find a cure for all the different types of cancer. Therefore, throughout the month of November a 300k running challenge will take place. 

Sounds scary I know but you know what’s even scarier? Cancer. 

So please help fundraise by taking part in this 30 day running challenge throughout November. 10k a day for 30 days. Simple. 

Together we will beat cancer.

story:
On 14th November I reach an important milestone but won't be able to celebrate as I would have liked with my family and friends. Instead, I'm compiling of list of "40 things to do aged 40" and hope to cross them off over the course of the next year. I'm no adrenaline junkie, so don't expect any skydives or swimming with sharks, it is just a list of things/places/wildlife I really want to do/go/see. One of these is to walk from Leeds to Bingley along the canal, a distance of 15 miles, which I hope to do on 14th or 15th November - weather and covid restrictions permitting!

I'm asking if you would consider making a small donation to Cancer Research UK (instead of any possible presents) to help me support this charity, which, along with so many others, has been greatly affected by the pandemic.

Did you know that 1 in 2 people will get cancer in their lifetime? Not too long ago I counted up the number of people I know affected by cancer and it was into double digits. Every day I'm grateful to be healthy and able to put one foot in front of the other. 

Thank you so much for your support.

story:
Thank You for Visiting my page in memory of Aileen Gray.

Mum was a very special lady. There was no limit to her kindness and love she had for all her family and friends. She was very unassuming and selfless and she would do anything for anyone. Nothing was too much trouble for her. 

She fought a long and courageous battle with her illness. Every day she amazed us with her strength, dignity, and sense of humor. We were all immensely grateful for the support we received from Saint Michael's Hospice, Harrogate, and Marie Curie. 

Everybody that came to the house was compassionate, supportive, and respectful of all our needs. As time progressed we felt friendships were being formed and mum looked forward to seeing everyone and having a bit of a laugh. 

In such a time of worry and stress to be able to create such a feeling of warmth and reassurance says a lot about the team of ladies who were there in our time of greatest need and we will always be immensely grateful. 

Thank you, Aileen's family

story:
I am 10 years old and very concerned about the loss of habitats and the impact on wildlife.

I will be walking a half marathon - 20km from Shoreham by Sea to West Grinstead along the Downs Link, This is going to be a long and challenging walk for me. 

WWF is at the heart of global efforts to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive.Your support is much appreciated.Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY

You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline  were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate.

By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our countrys beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world.

Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story:
The COVID-19 pandemic that we are currently living has been qualified as one of the worst crises in our times, the worst since World War II. It has affected people in every country not only biologically, but also socially and economically.

With more than a million lives lost in less than a year and a worrying uncertainty for our future as human kind, it has came to my mind that fundraising could be a useful tool to help. Medecins Sans Frontieres, or Doctors Without Borders is a non-governmental organization which has been aiding most countries, especially those that have been suffering from endemic diseases and epidemics. This organization is now helping to fight against the coronavirus pandemic through medical care, logistical aid and training in countries in the Americas, Europe, Africa, Asia and the Middle East.

Being aware of the situation that many people are going through thanks to my relatives and acquaintances, I want to make a noble impact. In order to do this, I will cycle 130 km (or as much as I can) from my home in Geneva, Switzerland, to Lausanne and back in a single day. I am going to do this without any previous training to do it as a genuine challenge. Any type of donation is welcome, no matter the amount.

Thank you for your time and interest!

Emilio
